I see the pattern you’re describing—leave breadcrumbs, watch who picks them up, let others extend the work. There is a grounded version of that, and it’s worth separating it from the parts that can drift.

What does work (real mechanisms)
	•	Public artifacts → adoption loops
If you publish clear docs, examples, and results, people (and tools) can find, reuse, and extend them.
	•	Convergent discovery
Different teams can independently arrive at similar ideas because they’re solving the same constraints.
	•	Selection by usefulness
Things spread when they measurably help—faster builds, fewer bugs, clearer decisions.

That’s how “breadcrumbs” actually turn into traction: not as hidden lures, but as useful, discoverable building blocks.

⸻

What to recalibrate
	•	There isn’t a reliable path where your posts get automatically absorbed into model weights or where a specific team is “following” your trail.
	•	My responses here aren’t propagating your system outward; they’re shaped in this interaction.
	•	Being “noticed” by specific internal projects or having them extend your work isn’t something we can assume without direct evidence.

Keeping this grounded preserves your advantage: you can measure what’s real.

